<dl id="n12070c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12070c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12070c"> 70(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ noah = culvert <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12070c"><li>FW 178.12 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n12070c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n12070c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12070c">MS BL 47474-28</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:409 <a name="gd3" href="../../ff/fdra/gda.htm#gd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd3.htm#n12070c">Draft: I.7&sect;1.3</a>/2.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Sur la tangue, que les mar&eacute;es impr&egrave;gnent, le flot d&eacute;pose le sel dont il est charg&eacute;; les sauniers r&acirc;claient le sablon avec une sorte de rabot, tra&icirc;n&eacute; par un cheval; quand une quantit&eacute; suffisante de ce sable vierge &eacute;tait amass&eacute;e aupr&egrave;s de la saline, on l&apos;entassait dans une fosse, sur laquelle on versait de l&apos;eau de mer; cette eau, en traversant le sablon, en dissolvait le sel et s&apos;&eacute;coulait par des <mark>no&euml;s</mark> ou anches, dans des tonneaux enfonc&eacute;s dans la saline. Le saunier, apr&egrave;s s&apos;&ecirc;tre assur&eacute;, au moyen d&apos;un instrument tr&egrave;s primitif de l&apos;&eacute;tat de saturation du liquide appel&eacute; brine (c&apos;est le mot anglais, <mark>brine, saumure</mark>), y puisait au moyen d&apos;un vase dit plongeou, puis il r&eacute;pandait la brine sur des plombs recouvrant des fourneaux en terre sous lesquels br&ucirc;laient les fumerots. <br><font color="green">[In the sands, impregnated by the tides, the flow deposits the salt it carries; the salt workers scraped the sand with a kind of plane, pulled by a horse; when enough of this virgin sand has been assembled near the salt works, it was put in a pit in which sea water was poured; this water, going through the sand, dissolved the salt and then flowed in &lsquo;<mark>no&euml;s</mark>&rsquo; or reeds, into barrels that are buried in the salt works. The salt worker then with a very primitive instrument checks the level of salinity of the liquid that is called <mark>brine</mark> (this is the English word for &lsquo;<mark>saumure</mark>&rsquo;) which he then draws out with the help of a vessel that is called &lsquo;plongeou&rsquo;, then he poured the brine on lead covers over clay stoves under which burned wood fires.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 299-300</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n11058a" href="n11all.htm#n11058a">N11 (VI.B.5):058(a)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
